DebugThugz_Module4

DebugThugz

2022-09-29

Introduction

The main theme of the project is to assess the morphological and allometric differences between ecomorphs within the genus Anolis. A recent study by Hagey et al. (2017) studied the hindlimb-ecomorph relationship in anoles. So, this project will determine if ecomorph is an important predictor of the hindlimb-SVL relationship in anoles by using phylogenetic least squares analysis to assess this relationship under Brownian motion and OU models of trait evolution.

An anolis lizard

Methods

To answer the question, two simple linear models were constructed that assess the effect of perch diameter and height, and the residuals of these models were plotted against ecomorph. Then, phylogenetic least squares models of hindlimb-SVL relationships with perch diameter and height were constructed based on the phylogenetic tree data (Poe et al. 2017). Each models fit was assessed with AICc and AICw to determine if one or both was a significant predictor of hindlimb length in a phylogenetic context.

Results

The results of this experiment showed that both perch height and diameter combined are significant predictors of hindlimb length in a phylogenetic context. Additionally, it was determined that ecomorph was an important predictor of the hindlimb-SVL relationship in anoles.

anole <- read_csv("anole.dat.EF.csv")
## Rows: 70 Columns: 3
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): Species
## dbl (2): SVL, HTotal
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
anole.eco <- read_csv("anole.eco.EF.csv")
## Rows: 70 Columns: 5
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (3): Species, Ecomorph, Ecomorph2
## dbl (2): PH, ArbPD
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
anole.tree <- read.tree("anole.EF.tre")

#chunks

anole2 <- anole%>%
left_join(anole.eco)%>%
  filter(!Ecomorph%in%c("U","CH"))%>%
  na.omit()
## Joining, by = "Species"
anole.log <- anole2%>%
  mutate_at(c("SVL", "HTotal","PH","ArbPD"),log)
### phylogenetic GLS models

#PGLS under BM, no ecomorph
pgls.BM1 <- gls(HTotal ~SVL, correlation = corBrownian(1,phy = anole.tree,form=~Species),data = anole.log, method = "ML")

#PGLS under BM, w ecomorph
pgls.BM2 <- gls(HTotal ~SVL * Ecomorph2, correlation = corBrownian(1,phy = anole.tree,form=~Species),data = anole.log, method = "ML")

#PGLS under OU, no ecomorph
pgls.OU1 <- gls(HTotal ~SVL, correlation = corMartins(0,phy = anole.tree,form=~Species),data = anole.log, method = "ML")

#PGLS under OU, w, ecomorph
pgls.OU2 <- gls(HTotal ~SVL * Ecomorph2, correlation = corMartins(0,phy = anole.tree,form=~Species),data = anole.log, method = "ML")
#AIC operations
anole.phylo.aic <- AICc(pgls.BM1,pgls.BM2,pgls.OU1,pgls.OU2)
anole.phylow.aicw <- aicw(anole.phylo.aic$AICc)
anole.phylo.aic%>%
  kable(caption="AIC of BM and OU PGLS Models Considering Ecomorph of *Anolis*")

#add phylo-corrected residuals
anole.log <- anole.log%>%
  mutate(phylo.res=residuals(pgls.BM2))
#Regression Plot
anole.log%>%
  ggplot(aes(HTotal,SVL,col=Ecomorph2))+geom_point()+geom_smooth(method="lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Regression Plot of Log-transformed HTotal vs. SVL by Ecomorphs 

#plot residuals
p.eco.phylo <- anole.log%>%
ggplot(aes(x=Ecomorph2,y=phylo.res)) +geom_boxplot() +stat_summary(fun=mean, geom="point", size=3)
print(p.eco.phylo)

Boxplot of phylogenetically corrected hindlimb residuals versus anole ecomorph

Discussion

The finding that ecomorph was an important predictor of the hindlimb-SVL relationship in anoles answers the initial question and is important because it shows that the ecological parameters of perch height and perch diameter predict discrete patterns in the hindlimb-SVL relationship.
